{"meta":{"domain":"subjects","kid":"1710","authors":[{"fullname":"Nicolas Tournadre","id":"6"}],"title":"","dates":{"created_at":"2013-09-15 04:07:31 UTC","updated_at":"2013-09-15 04:07:31 UTC"}},"nodes":[{"index":0,"parent_index":-1,"body":"<p class=\"Paragraph\">Traditional grammars refer to this mark as <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f56\u0fb1\u0f7a\u0f51\u0f0b\u0f66\u0f92\u0fb2\u0f0b<\/span>, literally \u201cagent-sound.\u201d The agentive indicates the agent of the action (\u201cby\u201d), the instrument (\u201cwith\u201d), the cause (\u201cbecause of,\u201d \u201cby\u201d), and the manner (\u201cwith\u201d); it also marks causal subordinate clauses, in which case it may be translated by \u201csince,\u201d \u201cbecause,\u201d etc.<\/p><p class=\"Paragraph\">The agentive is formed by adding a <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f66<\/span> to the genitive. The variants follow the same pattern as in the case of the genitive: <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f42\u0f72\u0f66\u0f0b<\/span>, <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f42\u0fb1\u0f72\u0f66\u0f0b<\/span>, <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f40\u0fb1\u0f72\u0f66\u0f0b<\/span>, <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f66\u0f0b<\/span>.<\/p><ul> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f66\u0f0b<\/span> is used after vowels and <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f60\u0f0b<\/span><\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f42\u0f72\u0f66\u0f0b<\/span> is used after <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f42\u0f0b<\/span>, <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f44\u0f0b<\/span><\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f40\u0fb1\u0f72\u0f66\u0f0b<\/span> is used after <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f51\u0f0b<\/span>, <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f56\u0f0b<\/span>, <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f66\u0f0b<\/span> and the <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f51\u0f0b\u0f51\u0fb2\u0f42\u0f0b<\/span><\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f42\u0fb1\u0f72\u0f66\u0f0b<\/span> is used after <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f53\u0f0b<\/span>, <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f58\u0f0b<\/span>, <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f62\u0f0b<\/span>, <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f63\u0f0b<\/span><\/li> <\/ul><p class=\"Paragraph\">In Classical Tibetan, vowels may also be followed by the variant <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f61\u0f72\u0f66\u0f0b<\/span>, or even by the more archaic form <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f60\u0f72\u0f66\u0f0b<\/span>.<\/p><p class=\"Paragraph\">The following table gives examples of how these variants are used.<\/p><table border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\"> <tbody> <tr> <td width=\"151\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f49\u0f72\u0f0b\u0f58\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cSun\u201d<\/p> <\/td> <td width=\"144\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f49\u0f72\u0f0b\u0f58\u0f66\u0f0b<\/span><\/p> <\/td> <\/tr> <tr> <td width=\"151\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f62\u0f72\u0f0b\u0f58\u0f7c\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cDrawing\u201d<\/p> <\/td> <td width=\"144\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f62\u0f72\u0f0b\u0f58\u0f7c\u0f66\u0f0b<\/span><\/p> <\/td> <\/tr> <tr> <td width=\"151\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f46\u0f74\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cWater\u201d<\/p> <\/td> <td width=\"144\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f46\u0f74\u0f66\u0f0b<\/span><\/p> <\/td> <\/tr> 